@donmccurdy You're also using the draco loader [here](https://github.com/donmccurdy/three-gltf-viewer/blob/5998675b6e5375bc17e851387cbcb34ededf3991/src/viewer.js#L188). I am not using in my setup since I am not importing compressed files, like it says in the three.js docs:

```js
// Optional: Provide a DRACOLoader instance to decode compressed mesh data
THREE.DRACOLoader.setDecoderPath( '/examples/js/libs/draco' );
loader.setDRACOLoader( new THREE.DRACOLoader() );
```

[Here is my loading setup if you want to take a look at it](https://github.com/marcofugaro/shrimpcat/blob/a72fa0ccd56a9eb42316e422bfb3598c5f7c94d9/src/lib/AssetManager.js#L146-L148)

But more simply the error is reproducible if you try to load the file like it says in the documentation, but without the draco loader:

```js
// Instantiate a loader
var loader = new THREE.GLTFLoader();

// Load a glTF resource
loader.load(
	// resource URL
	'models/van.gltf',
	// called when the resource is loaded
	function ( gltf ) {

		scene.add( gltf.scene );

		gltf.animations; // Array<THREE.AnimationClip>
		gltf.scene; // THREE.Scene
		gltf.scenes; // Array<THREE.Scene>
		gltf.cameras; // Array<THREE.Camera>
		gltf.asset; // Object

	},
	// called while loading is progressing
	function ( xhr ) {

		console.log( ( xhr.loaded / xhr.total * 100 ) + '% loaded' );

	},
	// called when loading has errors
	function ( error ) {

		console.log( 'An error happened' );

	}
);
```

Refarding the file process, I have downloaded the file from Sketchfab in `.fbx` format, imported in blender 2.8, made some modifications to it, and exported it in gltf 2.0.
